               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-347-person2862">
                  JAMES 
                  WILLIAM THOMPSON
               <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2862" type="surname" value="WILLIAM THOMPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2862" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2862" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at Poplar. On the 27th of March, about seven o'clock in the evening, I was near <placeName id="t18300415-347-crimeloc1878">Aldgate church</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-347-crimeloc1878" type="placeName" value="Aldgate church"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-347-crimeloc1878" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-347-off1876 t18300415-347-crimeloc1878"></join>, and felt a pull at my pocket - I turned round, and saw the prisoner in possession of my handkerchief, which was safe just before; I collared him, and was immediately surrounded by five or six persons, men and boys - I asked where I could get an officer; they directed me up an alley, and I was glad to get back again- I was surrounded by them, saying I had better let him go, as I should have so much trouble; but an officer came, and I delivered him over.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. A lady saw it drop from his pocket. Witness. I saw it drop from the prisoner's hand.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-347-person2863">
                  JAMES 
                  HALL
               <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2863" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2863" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2863" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable of Tower-ward. I took the prisoner near Aldgate church; there were a great many men and women in a waggon, going off to the Swan River, which caused a crowd.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I never saw the gentleman's handkerchief; I was walking by, when he turned round and said, "You are the lad;" he instantly collared me, and his handkerchief laid behind me - a lady came to the watch-house, and said she saw it fall from his pocket.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-347-person2864">
                  CAROLINE 
                  BAILEY
               <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2864" type="surname" value="BAILEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2864" type="given" value="CAROLINE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2864" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at No. 20, Princes-street, Baker's-row, Whitechapel, and live with my mother - I get my living by needle-work; I never knew the prisoner before this occurred. I saw Mr. Thompson drop his handkerchief, whether he was putting it into his pocket or taking it out, I do not know; but I saw him drop it - there were a number of people round a waggon; the prisoner was coming by at the time - Mr. Thompson caught hold of him by the arm and said, "I have got you, you have robbed me;" I said, "No, sir, he has not, indeed;" he said, "No, has not he?" I said, "No, sir, the handkerchief dropped from your pocket;" he said, "Well, we will see all about that," and conveyed the prisoner to the watch-house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-347-person2865">
                  WILLIAM 
                  THOMPSON
               <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2865" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2865" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2865" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw this witness; and she intimated to me that it had dropped from my pocket; but I saw the <rs id="t18300415-347-deflabel1879" type="occupation">boy</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-347-defend2859 t18300415-347-deflabel1879"></join> drop it, and immediately collared him, and took him up the alley - this young woman followed, and said, "You are mistaken in the boy."</p>
               <p>Q. Not that you was mistaken in his person, but mistaken in his being the thief? A. Yes.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-347-person2866">
                  CAROLINE 
                  BAILEY
               <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2866" type="surname" value="BAILEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2866" type="given" value="CAROLINE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-person2866" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I told him no such thing; no person was near his pocket at the time - I did not go before the Magistrate, as I thought the gentleman had declined it; and I knew the boy was not guilty - I told this story at the watch-house, and left word with the officer, where I was to be found.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300415-347-verdict1880" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-347-verdict1880" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
